name: Viua Virtual Machine
description: Virtual machine designed for reliability, concurrency, and background software.
contribution_justification: Projects on GitHub by default use issues and pull requests, as encouraged by documentation such as <https://guides.github.com/activities/contributing-to-open-source/>.
contribution_requirements_justification:

license_location_justification: Non-trivial license location file in repository: <https://github.com/marekjm/viuavm/blob/devel/LICENSE>.
floss_license_justification: The GPL-3.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The GPL-3.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_interface_justification:
Documentation for Viua VM (instruction set description, abstract model, etc.) is provided at https://docs.viuavm.org/
Additionally, each tool (assembler, disassembler, lexer, and kernel) each provide a documentation of their options and switches when invoked with the "--help" flag.
repo_public_justification: Repository on GitHub, which provides public git repositories with URLs.
repo_track_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_distributed_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.
release_notes_justification: Non-trivial release notes file in repository: <https://github.com/marekjm/viuavm/blob/devel/Changelog.markdown>.
release_notes_vulns_justification: Release notes include a list of all fixes that are included in each release. Viua is not popular enough to attract attention of either security community, or the cracker crowd, so the only "security" related vulnerabilities that are found are ordinary bugs.
report_process_justification:
Bugs are submitted using GitHub's issue mechanism.

https://github.com/marekjm/viuavm/issues
report_responses_justification: Bugs reported through the GitHub's issue tracker are addressed quickly (usually in a matter or days).
report_archive_justification:
Bugs are submitted using GitHub's issue mechanism is used for this purpose.

https://github.com/marekjm/viuavm/issues?q=is%3Aissue+is%3Aclosed can be browsed to access past issues.
vulnerability_report_process_justificati: Vulnerability reporting process is described in contributor guidelines: http://git.savannah.nongnu.org/cgit/viuavm.git/tree/CONTRIBUTING.markdown?h=devel
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: All vulnerabilities are reported publicly, as bugs.
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: No vulnerabilities were reported in last 6 months.
build_floss_tools_justification: At the extreme minimum, Viua requires only a C++ compiler to be built (both GCC and Clang work).
test_justification: Viua provides a set of about 400 tests in a "quick" and "heavy" (i.e. run under Valgrind, with double runs for dis- and reassembled code) modes.
test_invocation_justification: Use "make test" to launch test suite.
test_most_justification: Test suite covers most instructions available to the software running on the VM.
warnings_justification: Viua uses an almost painful set of compiler flags (which sometimes results in Voodoo dancing to satisfy the compilers), and is compilable under GCC and Clang to get feedback from different compilers.
warnings_fixed_justification: Viua compiles without a single warning under GCC.
warnings_strict_justification: The code includes Voodoo dancing to satisfy the compilers, but compiles under excruciating set of warning flags.
know_secure_design_justification:
The VM abstracts the platform way to some extent (so provides a layer of separation) and verifies actions performed by the software for errors, but inevitably *must* allow *everything* the software would like to do. It is not the VM's responsibility to prevent the user running the software from deleting files of other users, or from writing files larger than 1TB to disk - it is operating system's responsibility. The VM is not in a position to judge the actions of the software it is running.

Thus, this requirement is met, but on a slightly different basis - the VM is "secure" because of rigorous testing, warning-free compilation, and the fact that ASan, LSan, and UBSan do not report errors for it.
delivery_mitm_justification: Packed archives can be downloaded over HTTPS, Git repositories can be cloned using SSH.
delivery_unsigned_justification: Release tarballs are available over HTTPS: https://release.viuavm.org/
vulnerabilities_fixed_60_days_justificat: There are no reported vulnerabilities for Viua VM, as it is not a widely-used piece of software. The code is expected to have low number of open vulnerabilities due to heavy use of testing and instrumentation during the development process.
static_analysis_fixed_justification: Clang static analyser is used did not find any bugs in Viua VM's code.
dynamic_analysis_justification: Test suite is run under Valgrind, and with ASan, LSan, and UBSan enabled.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: Viua VM does not produce warnings under ASan, LSan, UBSan, and Valgrind.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: AddressSanitizer, LeakSanitizer, and Undefined-BehaviourSanitizer are used in the default test build.
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: Viua compiles and tests without a single warning from ASan, LSan, UBSan, and Valgrind. Code is not allowed to be merged into devel or master branches if it raises even a single warning.
general_comments: Viua VM is not an ordinary end-user application (for the typical definition of an "end-user"). It is an environment which programmers may use to write software, and - due to its nature - it may not be particularly suitable for writing user-facing front-end parts of the software. Thus, when the guidelines here are concerned about end-user related concepts they may be "Unmet", bit it is not harmful for the project.
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests.
no_leaked_credentials_justification: Viua public repositories do not contain any credentials.
hardening_justification: Viua VM compiles without a single compiler warning, and warnings are treated as errors. Also, Viua VM does not trigger any warnings when run under ASan, LSan, UBSan, or Valgrind.
hardened_site_justification: X-Content-Type-Options was not set to "nosniff".
documentation_quick_start_justification:
The "How to write the 'Hello World!'" guide is located here: https://github.com/marekjm/viuavm#hello-world-in-viua-vm
Also, quick-start documentation is available at: https://docs.viuavm.org/requirements-and-build-process.html
documentation_current_justification: The documentation is provided at: https://docs.viuavm.org/ and is updated on a best-effort basis.
documentation_achievements_justification: Badges are prominently displayed on the README page: https://github.com/marekjm/viuavm#viua-vm-
accessibility_best_practices_justificati: All project websites use very simple CSS that relies on user's browser settings instead of pushing a "vision" of how the site should be viewed. Users can freely adjust font-sizes and colours, and the sites remain readable.
internationalization_justification: The VM runs binary code that is not intended for human consumption. The assembly language mnemonics are in English, and it would not be feasible to internationalise them.
sites_password_security_justification: No project site stores any passwords.
maintenance_or_update_justification: Viua is still in alpha stage of development, so the point about maintaining backwards compatibility does not really apply.
coding_standards_enforced_justification: Clang-format is used to enforce coding style. http://git.savannah.nongnu.org/cgit/viuavm.git/tree/.clang-format?h=devel
build_standard_variables_justification: Provided Makefile honors required environment variables.
build_preserve_debug_justification: By default, Viua builds with debugging information left untouched.
build_non_recursive_justification: Only a single Makefile is used.
automated_integration_testing_justificat: Test suite runs more than 400 tests: http://git.savannah.nongnu.org/cgit/viuavm.git/tree/tests/tests.py?h=devel
regression_tests_added50_justification: Most bugs land as new test cases in sampe/ directory in the repository.
input_validation_justification: The project is a VM. It assumes the source code is written by a programmer and does not contain garbage. When bytecode is running the VM throws exceptions on invalid actions taken by the user software.
copyright_per_file_justification: Every file in the repository has a copyright statement, which includes the information the the license used is "GNU GPL v3 or any later version".
license_per_file_justification: Every file in the repository has a copyright statement, which includes the information the the license used is "GNU GPL v3 or any later version".

name: Duo Authentication Proxy in a docker container
description:
Duo Authentication Proxy provides a local proxy service to enable on-premise integrations between VPNs, devices, applications, and hosted Duo or Trustwave two-factor authentication (2fa).

This repo provides a way to build Duo Authentication Proxy into a docker image and run it as a container.
contribution_justification: Non-trivial contribution file in repository: <https://github.com/jumanjihouse/docker-duoauthproxy/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md>.
license_location_justification: Non-trivial license location file in repository: <https://github.com/jumanjihouse/docker-duoauthproxy/blob/master/LICENSE>.

version_unique_justification:
https://github.com/jumanjihouse/docker-duoauthproxy#pull-an-already-built-image

The "latest" tag always points to the latest version. In general, you should prefer to use a pessimistic (i.e., specific) tag. The runtime image on Docker hub has tags that match:

    <upstream_authproxy_version>-<build_date>T<build_time>-<git_hash>

These tags allow to correlate any image to the upstream authproxy version (semver), the build date and time, and the git commit from this repo that was used to build the image.
version_tags_justification: each release is built by CI and published to docker hub with tag that includes upstream version number, build date and time, plus git hash of this repo
release_notes_justification: readme (https://github.com/jumanjihouse/docker-duoauthproxy#duo-authproxy-on-linux) includes prominent link to upstream release notes (https://duo.com/support/documentation/authproxy-notes)
release_notes_vulns_justification: upstream release notes (https://duo.com/support/documentation/authproxy-notes) list every product security announcement, plus the readme in this project links to the most recent PSA and specifies minimum version to be protected

the entire build is done within open-source docker container with open-source tools
